      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Why EDTA is so much stronger\n\nThe ~9 log-unit advantage of EDTA over NTA reflects the **chelate effect** and **denticity difference**. EDTA is a hexadentate ligand (2 N + 4 carboxylate O donors) that wraps completely around Fe³⁺, whereas NTA is only tetradentate (1 N + 3 carboxylate O donors). The two additional donor groups in EDTA provide extra coordination bonds and a much larger favorable entropy change (ΔS = 443 vs 350 J/mol·K), which is the dominant thermodynamic driving force for both complexes. This enormous stability difference is why EDTA is the preferred chelator in analytical chemistry (e.g., complexometric titrations of Fe³⁺) and in industrial applications for iron sequestration.\n\n---\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
